# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: design-for-test
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] A defect is an error caused in a device during the manufacturing process.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] A fault model is a mathematical description of how a defect alters design behavior.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] The logic values observed at the device's primary outputs, while applying a test pattern to some device under test (DUT), are called the output of that test pattern.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] The output of a test pattern, when testing a fault-free device that works exactly as designed, is called the expected output of that test pattern.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] A fault is said to be *detected* by a test pattern if the output of that test pattern, when testing a device that has only that one fault, is different than the expected output.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] The ATPG process for a targeted fault consists of two phases: *fault activation* and *fault propagation*.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Fault activation establishes a signal value at the fault model site that is opposite of the value produced by the fault model.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Fault propagation moves the resulting signal value, or fault effect, forward by sensitizing a path from the fault site to a primary output.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] ATPG can fail to find a test for a particular fault in at least two cases.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] First, the fault may be intrinsically undetectable, such that no patterns exist that can detect that particular fault.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] The classic example of this is a redundant circuit, designed such that no single fault causes the output to change.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] In such a circuit, any single fault will be inherently undetectable.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Second, it is possible that a detection pattern exists, but the algorithm cannot find one.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Since the ATPG problem is NP-complete (by reduction from the Boolean satisfiability problem) there will be cases where patterns exist, but ATPG gives up as it will take too long to find them (assuming P≠NP, of course).
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Equivalent faults produce the same faulty behavior for all input patterns.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Any single fault from the set of equivalent faults can represent the whole set.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] In this case, much less than *k×n* fault tests are required for a circuit with *n* signal line.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Removing equivalent faults from entire set of faults is called fault collapsing.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] In the past several decades, the most popular fault model used in practice is the single stuck-at fault model.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] In this model, one of the signal lines in a circuit is assumed to be stuck at a fixed logic value, regardless of what inputs are supplied to the circuit.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Hence, if a circuit has *n* signal lines, there are potentially *2n* stuck-at faults defined on the circuit, of which some can be viewed as being equivalent to others.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] The stuck-at fault model is a *logical* fault model because no delay information is associated with the fault definition.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] The single stuck-at fault model is *structural* because it is defined based on a structural gate-level circuit model.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] A pattern set with 100% stuck-at fault coverage consists of tests to detect every possible stuck-at fault in a circuit.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] 100% stuck-at fault coverage does not necessarily guarantee high quality, since faults of many other kinds often occur (e.g. bridging faults, opens faults, delay faults).
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] This model is used to describe faults for CMOS logic gates.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] At transistor level, a transistor maybe stuck-short or stuck-open.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] In stuck-short, a transistor behaves as it is always conducts (or stuck-on), and stuck-open is when a transistor never conducts current (or stuck-off).
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Stuck-short will produce a short between VDD and VSS.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] A short circuit between two signal lines is called bridging faults.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Bridging to VDD or Vss is equivalent to stuck at fault model.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Traditionally both signals after bridging were modeled with logic AND or OR of both signals.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] If one driver dominates the other driver in a bridging situation, the dominant driver forces the logic to the other one, in such case a dominant bridging fault is used.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] To better reflect the reality of CMOS VLSI devices, a Dominant AND or Dominant OR bridging fault model is used.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] In the latter case, dominant driver keeps its value, while the other one gets the AND or OR value of its own and the dominant driver.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] The combinational ATPG method allows testing the individual nodes (or flip-flops) of the logic circuit without being concerned with the operation of the overall circuit.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] During test, a so-called scan-mode is enabled forcing all flip-flops (FFs) to be connected in a simplified fashion, effectively bypassing their interconnections as intended during normal operation.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] This allows using a relatively simple vector matrix to quickly test all the comprising FFs, as well as to trace failures to specific FFs.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Sequential-circuit ATPG searches for a sequence of test vectors to detect a particular fault through the space of all possible test vector sequences.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Various search strategies and heuristics have been devised to find a shorter sequence, or to find a sequence faster.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] However, according to reported results, no single strategy or heuristic out-performs others for all applications or circuits.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] This observation implies that a test generator should include a comprehensive set of heuristics.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Even a simple stuck-at fault requires a sequence of vectors for detection in a sequential circuit.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Also, due to the presence of memory elements, the controllability and observability of the internal signals in a sequential circuit are in general much more difficult than those in a combinational logic circuit.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] These factors make the complexity of sequential ATPG much higher than that of combinational ATPG, where a scan-chain (i.e. switchable, for-test-only signal chain) is added to allow simple access to the individual nodes.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Due to the high complexity of the sequential ATPG, it remains a challenging task for large, highly sequential circuits that do not incorporate any Design For Testability (DFT) scheme.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] However, these test generators, combined with low-overhead DFT techniques such as partial scan, have shown a certain degree of success in testing large designs.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] For designs that are sensitive to area or performance overhead, the solution of using sequential-circuit ATPG and partial scan offers an attractive alternative to the popular full-scan solution, which is based on combinational-circuit ATPG.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Historically, ATPG has focused on a set of faults derived from a gate-level fault model.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] As design trends move toward nanometer technology, new manufacture testing problems are emerging.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] During design validation, engineers can no longer ignore the effects of crosstalk and power supply noise on reliability and performance.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Current fault modeling and vector-generation techniques are giving way to new models and techniques that consider timing information during test generation, that are scalable to larger designs, and that can capture extreme design conditions.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] For nanometer technology, many current design validation problems are becoming manufacturing test problems as well, so new fault-modeling and ATPG techniques will be needed.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Testing very-large-scale integrated circuits with a high fault coverage is a difficult task because of complexity.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] Therefore, many different ATPG methods have been developed to address combinational and sequential circuits.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] ATPG is a topic that is covered by several conferences throughout the year.
[src:design-for-test/automatic-test-pattern-generation] The primary US conferences are the International Test Conference and The VLSI Test Symposium, while in Europe the topic is covered by DATE and ETS.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] The Joint Test Action Group (JTAG) developed a specification for boundary scan testing that was standardized in 1990 as the IEEE Std.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] In 1994, a supplement that contains a description of the boundary scan description language (BSDL) was added which describes the boundary-scan logic content of IEEE Std 1149.1 compliant devices.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Since then, this standard has been adopted by electronic device companies all over the world.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Boundary scan is now mostly synonymous with JTAG.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Each test cell may be programmed via the JTAG scan chain to drive a signal onto a pin and thus across an individual trace on the board; the cell at the destination of the board trace can then be read, verifying that the board trace properly connects the two pins.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] If the trace is shorted to another signal or if the trace is open, the correct signal value does not show up at the destination pin, indicating a fault.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] To provide the boundary scan capability, IC vendors add additional logic to each of their devices, including *scan cells* for each of the external traces.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] These cells are then connected together to form the external boundary scan shift register (BSR), and combined with JTAG Test Access Port (TAP) controller support comprising four (or sometimes more) additional pins plus control circuitry.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Some TAP controllers support scan chains between on-chip logical design blocks, with JTAG instructions which operate on those internal scan chains instead of the BSR.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] This can allow those integrated components to be tested as if they were separate chips on a board.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] On-chip debugging solutions are heavy users of such internal scan chains.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] These designs are part of most Verilog or VHDL libraries.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Overhead for this additional logic is minimal, and generally is well worth the price to enable efficient testing at the board level.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] For normal operation, the added boundary scan latch cells are set so that they have no effect on the circuit, and are therefore effectively invisible.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] However, when the circuit is set into a test mode, the latches enable a data stream to be shifted from one latch into the next.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Once a complete data word has been shifted into the circuit under test, it can be latched into place so it drives external signals.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Shifting the word also generally returns the input values from the signals configured as inputs.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] As the cells can be used to force data into the board, they can set up test conditions.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] The relevant states can then be fed back into the test system by clocking the data word back so that it can be analyzed.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] By adopting this technique, it is possible for a test system to gain test access to a board.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] As most of today's boards are very densely populated with components and tracks, it is very difficult for test systems to physically access the relevant areas of the board to enable them to test the board.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Boundary scan makes access possible without always needing physical probes.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] In modern chip and board design, design for test is a significant issue, and one common design artifact is a set of boundary scan test vectors, possibly delivered in Serial Vector Format (SVF) or a similar interchange format.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Devices communicate to the world via a set of input and output pins.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] By themselves, these pins provide limited visibility into the workings of the device.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] However, devices that support boundary scan contain a shift-register cell for each signal pin of the device.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] These registers are connected in a dedicated path around the device's boundary (hence the name).
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] The path creates a virtual access capability that circumvents the normal inputs and provides direct control of the device and detailed visibility at its outputs.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] The contents of the boundary scan are usually described by the manufacturer using a part-specific BSDL file.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Among other things, a BSDL file will describe each digital signal exposed through pin or ball (depending on the chip packaging) exposed in the boundary scan, as part of its definition of the Boundary Scan Register (BSR).
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] There are JTAG instructions to SAMPLE the data in that boundary scan register, or PRELOAD it with values.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] During testing, I/O signals enter and leave the chip through the boundary-scan cells.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Testing involves a number of test vectors, each of which drives some signals and then verifies that the responses are as expected.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] The boundary-scan cells can be configured to support external testing for interconnection between chips (EXTEST instruction) or internal testing for logic within the chip (INTEST instruction).
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Typically high-end commercial JTAG testing systems allow the import of design 'netlists' from CAD/EDA systems plus the BSDL models of boundary scan/JTAG compliant devices to automatically generate test applications.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] When used during manufacturing, such systems also support non-test but affiliated applications such as in-system programming of various types of flash memory: NOR, NAND, and serial (I2C or SPI).
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Such commercial systems are used by board test professionals and will often cost several thousand dollars for a fully-fledged system.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] They can include diagnostic options to accurately pin-point faults such as open circuits and shorts and may also offer schematic or layout viewers to depict the fault in a graphical manner.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Tests developed with such tools are frequently combined with other test systems such as in-circuit testers (ICTs) or functional board test systems.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] The boundary scan architecture also provides functionality which helps developers and engineers during development stages of an embedded system.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] A JTAG Test Access Port (TAP) can be turned into a low-speed logic analyzer.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] Angell at Stanford University proposed serial testing.
[src:design-for-test/boundary-scan] IBM developed level-sensitive scan design (LSSD).
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] A **built-in self-test** (**BIST**) or **built-in test** (**BIT**) is a mechanism that permits a machine to test itself.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] The main purpose of BIST is to reduce the complexity, and thereby decrease the cost and reduce reliance upon external (pattern-programmed) test equipment.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] 2. reduces the complexity of the test/probe setup, by reducing the number of I/O signals that must be driven/examined under tester control.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Both lead to a reduction in hourly charges for automated test equipment (ATE) service.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] BIST is commonly placed in weapons, avionics, medical devices, automotive electronics, complex machinery of all types, unattended machinery of all types, and integrated circuits.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Automotive tests itself to enhance safety and reliability.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] For example, most vehicles with antilock brakes test them once per safety interval.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] If the antilock brake system has a broken wire or other fault, the brake system reverts to operating as a normal brake system.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Most automotive engine controllers incorporate a "limp mode" for each sensor, so that the engine will continue to operate if the sensor or its wiring fails.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Another, more trivial example of a limp mode is that some cars test door switches, and automatically turn lights on using seat-belt occupancy sensors if the door switches fail.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Almost all avionics now incorporate BIST.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] In avionics, the purpose is to isolate failing line-replaceable units, which are then removed and repaired elsewhere, usually in depots or at the manufacturer.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Commercial aircraft only make money when they fly, so they use BIST to minimize the time on the ground needed for repair and to increase the level of safety of the system which contains BIST.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Similar arguments apply to military aircraft.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] When BIST is used in flight, a fault causes the system to switch to an alternative mode or equipment that still operates.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Critical flight equipment is normally duplicated, or redundant.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Less critical flight equipment, such as entertainment systems, might have a "limp mode" that provides some functions.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Built-in self-test is used to make faster, less-expensive integrated circuit manufacturing tests.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] The IC has a function that verifies all or a portion of the internal functionality of the IC.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] In some cases, this is valuable to customers, as well.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] For example, a BIST mechanism is provided in advanced fieldbus systems to verify functionality.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] At a high level this can be viewed similar to the PC BIOS's power-on self-test (POST) that performs a self-test of the RAM and buses on power-up.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] The typical personal computer tests itself at start-up because it's a very complex piece of machinery.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Since it includes a computer, a computerized self-test was an obvious, inexpensive feature.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Most modern computers, including embedded systems, have self-tests of their computer, memory and software.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Unattended machinery performs self-tests to discover whether it needs maintenance or repair.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Typical tests are for temperature, humidity, bad communications, burglars, or a bad power supply.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] For example, power systems or batteries are often under stress, and can easily overheat or fail.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Often the communication test is a critical item in a remote system.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] One of the most common unattended system is the telephone concentrator box.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] This contains complex electronics to accumulate telephone lines or data and route it to a central switch.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Telephone concentrators test for communications continuously, by verifying the presence of periodic data patterns called frames (See SONET).
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Frames repeat about 8,000 times per second.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Remote systems often have tests to loop back the communications locally, to test transmitter and receiver, and remotely, to test the communication link without using the computer or software at the remote unit.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Where electronic loop-backs are absent, the software usually provides the facility.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] For example, IP defines a local address which is a software loopback (IP-Address 127.0.0.1, usually locally mapped to name "localhost").
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Many remote systems have automatic reset features to restart their remote computers.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] These can be triggered by lack of communications, improper software operation or other critical events.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Satellites have automatic reset, and add automatic restart systems for power and attitude control, as well.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Medical devices test themselves to assure their continued safety.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] A POST will perform a comprehensive test.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Then, a periodic test will assure that the device has not become unsafe since the POST.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Safety-critical devices normally define a "safety interval", a period of time too short for injury to occur.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] The self test of the most critical functions normally is completed at least once per safety interval.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] The periodic test is normally a subset of the POST.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] One of the first computer-controlled BIST systems was in the U.S.'s Minuteman Missile.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Using an internal computer to control the testing reduced the weight of cables and connectors for testing.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] The Minuteman was one of the first major weapons systems to field a permanently installed computer-controlled self-test.
[src:design-for-test/built-in-self-test] Engineers specify the requirements, design, implementation, and verification of the built-in self-test mechanism in a BIT (or BIST) specification.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Tests are applied at several steps in the hardware manufacturing flow and, for certain products, may also be used for hardware maintenance in the customer's environment.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The tests are generally driven by test programs that execute using automatic test equipment (ATE) or, in the case of system maintenance, inside the assembled system itself.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] In addition to finding and indicating the presence of defects (i.e., the test fails), tests may be able to log diagnostic information about the nature of the encountered test failures.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The diagnostic information can be used to locate the source of the failure.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] In other words, the response of vectors (patterns) from a good circuit is compared with the response of vectors (using the same patterns) from a DUT (device under test).
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] If the response is the same or matches, the circuit is good.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Otherwise, the circuit is not manufactured as intended.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] DFT plays an important role in the development of test programs and as an interface for test applications and diagnostics.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Automatic test pattern generation (ATPG) is much easier if appropriate DFT rules and suggestions have been implemented.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] DFT techniques have been used at least since the early days of electric/electronic data processing equipment.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Early examples from the 1940s/50s are the switches and instruments that allowed an engineer to "scan" (i.e., selectively probe) the voltage/current at some internal nodes in an analog computer [analog scan].
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] DFT often is associated with design modifications that provide improved access to internal circuit elements such that the local internal state can be controlled (controllability) and/or observed (observability) more easily.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The design modifications can be strictly physical in nature (e.g., adding a physical probe point to a net) or add active circuit elements to facilitate controllability/observability (e.g., inserting a multiplexer into a net).
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] While controllability and observability improvements for internal circuit elements definitely are important for test, they are not the only type of DFT.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Other guidelines, for example, deal with the electromechanical characteristics of the interface between the product under test and the test equipment.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Examples are guidelines for the size, shape, and spacing of probe points, or the suggestion to add a high-impedance state to drivers attached to probed nets such that the risk of damage from back-driving is mitigated.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Over the years the industry has developed and used a large variety of more or less detailed and more or less formal guidelines for desired and/or mandatory DFT circuit modifications.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Much of the related body of DFT knowledge focuses on digital circuits, while DFT for analog/mixed-signal circuits takes somewhat of a backseat.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] DFT affects and depends on the methods used for test development, test application, and diagnostics.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Most tool-supported DFT practiced in the industry today, at least for digital circuits, is predicated on a *Structural test* paradigm.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Structural test makes no direct attempt to determine if the overall functionality of the circuit is correct.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Instead, it tries to make sure that the circuit has been assembled correctly from some low-level building blocks as specified in a structural netlist.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] For example, are all specified logic gates present, operating correctly, and connected correctly?
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The stipulation is that if the netlist is correct and structural testing has confirmed the correct assembly of the circuit elements, then the circuit should be functioning correctly.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Note that this is very different from *functional testing*, which attempts to validate that the circuit under test functions according to its functional specification.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] This is closely related to the functional verification problem of determining if the circuit specified by the netlist meets the functional specifications, assuming it is built correctly.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] One benefit of the Structural paradigm is that test generation can focus on testing a limited number of relatively simple circuit elements rather than having to deal with an exponentially exploding multiplicity of functional states and state transitions.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] While the task of testing a single logic gate at a time sounds simple, there is an obstacle to overcome.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] For today's highly complex designs, most gates are deeply embedded whereas the test equipment is only connected to the primary Input/outputs (I/Os) and/or some physical test points.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The embedded gates, hence, must be manipulated through intervening layers of logic.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] If the intervening logic contains state elements, then the issue of an exponentially exploding state space and state transition sequencing creates an unsolvable problem for test generation.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] To simplify test generation, DFT addresses the accessibility problem by removing the need for complicated state transition sequences when trying to control and/or observe what's happening at some internal circuit element.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Depending on the DFT choices made during circuit design/implementation, the generation of Structural tests for complex logic circuits can be more or less automated or self-automated.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] One key objective of DFT methodologies, hence, is to allow designers to make trade-offs between the amount and type of DFT and the cost/benefit (time, effort, quality) of the test generation task.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Another benefit is to diagnose a circuit in case any problem emerges in the future.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] It is like adding some features or provisions in the design so that devices can be tested in case of any fault during its use.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] One challenge for the industry is keeping up with the rapid advances in chip technology (I/O count/size/placement/spacing, I/O speed, internal circuit count/speed/power, thermal control, etc.) without being forced to continually upgrade the test equipment.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Modern DFT techniques, hence, have to offer options that allow next-generation chips and assemblies to be tested on existing test equipment and/or reduce the requirements/cost for new test equipment.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] As a result, DFT techniques are continually being updated, such as incorporation of compression, in order to make sure that tester application times stay within certain bounds dictated by the cost target for the products under test.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Especially for advanced semiconductor technologies, it is expected that some of the chips on each manufactured wafer contain defects that render them non-functional.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The primary objective of testing is to find and separate those non-functional chips from the fully functional ones, meaning that one or more responses captured by the tester from a non-functional chip under test differ from the expected response.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The percentage of chips that fail testing, hence, should be closely related to the expected functional yield for that chip type.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] In reality, however, it is not uncommon that all chips of a new chip type arriving at the test floor for the first time fail (so-called zero-yield situation).
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] In that case, the chips have to go through a debug process that tries to identify the reason for the zero-yield situation.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] In other cases, the test fall-out (percentage of test failures) may be higher than expected/acceptable or fluctuate suddenly.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Again, the chips have to be subjected to an analysis process to identify the reason for the excessive test fall-out.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] In both cases, vital information about the nature of the underlying problem may be hidden in the way the chips fail during testing.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] To facilitate better analysis, additional failure information beyond a simple pass/fail is collected into a fail log.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The fail log typically contains information about when (e.g., tester cycle), where (e.g., at what tester channel), and how (e.g., logic value) the test failed.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Diagnostics attempt to derive from the fail log at which logical/physical location inside the chip the problem most likely started.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] By running a large number of failures through the diagnostics process, called volume diagnostics, systematic failures can be identified.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] In some cases (e.g., printed circuit boards, multi-chip modules (MCMs), embedded or stand-alone memories) it may be possible to repair a failing circuit under test.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] For that purpose, diagnostics must quickly find the failing unit and create a work order for repairing or replacing the failing unit.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] DFT approaches can be more or less diagnostics-friendly.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The related objectives of DFT are to facilitate or simplify failure data collection and diagnostics to an extent that can enable intelligent failure analysis (FA) sample selection, as well as improve the cost, accuracy, speed, and throughput of diagnostics and FA.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The most common method for delivering test data from chip inputs to internal *circuits under test* (CUTs, for short), and observing their outputs, is called scan-design.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] In scan design, registers (flip-flops or latches) in the design are connected in one or more scan chains, which are used to gain access to internal nodes of the chip.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Test patterns are shifted in via the scan chain(s), functional clock signals are pulsed to test the circuit during the "capture cycle(s)", and the results are then shifted out to chip output pins and compared against the expected "good machine" results.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Straightforward application of scan techniques can result in large vector sets with corresponding long tester time and memory requirements.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Test compression techniques address this problem by decompressing the scan input on chip and compressing the test output.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Large gains are possible since any particular test vector usually only needs to set and/or examine a small fraction of the scan chain bits.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The output of a scan design may be provided in forms such as Serial Vector Format (SVF), to be executed by test equipment.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] In addition to being useful for manufacturing "go/no go" testing, scan chains can also be used to "debug" chip designs.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] In this context, the chip is exercised in normal "functional mode" (for example, a computer or mobile phone chip might execute assembly language instructions).
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] At any time, the chip clock can be stopped, and the chip re-configured into "test mode".
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] At this point, the full internal state can be dumped out or set to any desired values by use of the scan chains.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] Another use of scan to aid debugging consists of scanning in an initial state to all memory elements and then go back to functional mode to perform system debugging.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] The advantage is to bring the system to a known state without going through many clock cycles.
[src:design-for-test/design-for-testing] This use of scan chains, along with the clock control circuits, is a related sub-discipline of logic design called *design for debug* or *design for debuggability*.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] A **fault model** is an engineering model of something that could go wrong in the construction or operation of a piece of equipment.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] From the model, the designer or user can then predict the consequences of this particular fault.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] Fault models can be used in almost all branches of engineering.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] There are two main ways for collapsing fault sets into smaller sets.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] It is possible that two or more faults produce same faulty behavior for all input patterns.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] These faults are called equivalent faults.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] In this case, much less than k×n fault tests are required for a circuit with n signal line. removing equivalent faults from entire set of faults is called fault collapsing. fault collapsing significantly decreases the number of faults to check.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] In the example diagram, red faults are equivalent to the faults that being pointed to with the arrows, so those red faults can be removed from the circuit.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] In this case, the fault collapse ratio is 12/20.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] Fault F is called dominant to F' if all tests of F' detects F.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] In this case, F can be removed from the fault list.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] If F dominates F' and F' dominates F, then these two faults are equivalent.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] In the example, a NAND gate has been shown, the set of all input values that can test output's SA0 is {00,01,10}. the set of all input values that can check first input's SA1 is {01}.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] In this case, output SA0 fault is dominant and can be removed from fault list.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] Two faults are functionally equivalent if they produce identical faulty functions or we can say, two faults are functionally equivalent if we can not distinguish them at primary outputs (PO) with any input test vector.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] A fault model in an aerospace context is a set of structured information which helps users or systems to identify and isolate a problem that occurs on an engine, line-replaceable unit (LRU), or auxiliary power unit (APU) during a flight.
[src:design-for-test/fault-model] Associated with this fault model may be a suggested repair procedure along with references to aircraft maintenance manuals (~ Light maintenance manual).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] JTAG implements standards for on-chip instrumentation in electronic design automation (EDA) as a complementary tool to digital simulation.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] It specifies the use of a dedicated debug port implementing a serial communications interface for low-overhead access without requiring direct external access to the system address and data buses.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The interface connects to an on-chip **Test Access Port** (TAP) that implements a stateful protocol to access a set of test registers that present chip logic levels and device capabilities of various parts.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The Joint Test Action Group formed in 1985 to develop a method of verifying designs and testing printed circuit boards after manufacture.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In 1990, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers codified the results of the effort in IEEE Standard 1149.1-1990, entitled *Standard Test Access Port and Boundary-Scan Architecture*.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The JTAG standards have been extended by multiple semiconductor chip manufacturers with specialized variants to provide vendor-specific features.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In the 1980s, multi-layer circuit boards and integrated circuits (ICs) using ball grid array and similar mounting technologies were becoming standard, and connections were being made between ICs that were not available to probes.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The majority of manufacturing and field faults in circuit boards were due to poor solder joints on the boards, imperfections among board connections, or the bonds and bond wires from IC pads to pin lead frames.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The Joint Test Action Group (JTAG) was formed in 1985 to provide a pins-out view from one IC pad to another so these faults could be discovered.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The industry standard became an IEEE standard in 1990 as IEEE Std.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In the same year, Intel released their first processor with JTAG (the 80486), which led to quicker industry adoption by all manufacturers.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In 1994, a supplement that contains a description of the boundary scan description language (BSDL) was added.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Further refinements regarding the use of all-zeros for EXTEST, separating the use of SAMPLE from PRELOAD and better implementation for OBSERVE_ONLY cells were made and released in 2001.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Since 1990, this standard has been adopted by electronics companies around the world.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Boundary scan is now mostly synonymous with JTAG, but JTAG has essential uses beyond such manufacturing applications.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] 1149.1 has introduced a vast set of optional features, associated extensions to BSDL, and a new procedural description language (PDL) based on Tcl.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Although JTAG's early applications targeted board-level testing, here the JTAG standard was designed to assist with device, board, and system testing, diagnosis, and fault isolation.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Today JTAG is used as the primary means of accessing sub-blocks of integrated circuits, making it an essential mechanism for debugging embedded systems which might not have any other debug-capable communications channel.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] On most systems, JTAG-based debugging is available from the very first instruction after CPU reset, letting it assist with development of early boot software which runs before anything is set up.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] An in-circuit emulator (or, more correctly, a *JTAG adapter*) uses JTAG as the transport mechanism to access on-chip debug modules inside the target CPU.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Those modules let software developers debug the software of an embedded system directly at the machine instruction level when needed, or (more typically) in terms of high-level language source code.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] System software debug support is for many software developers the main reason to be interested in JTAG.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Multiple silicon architectures, such as PowerPC, MIPS, ARM, and x86, built an entire software debug, instruction tracing, and data tracing infrastructure around the basic JTAG protocol.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Frequently, individual silicon vendors, however, only implement parts of these extensions.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Some examples are ARM CoreSight and Nexus as well as Intel's BTS (Branch Trace Storage), LBR (Last Branch Record), and IPT (Intel Processor Trace) implementations.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] There are a number of other such silicon vendor-specific extensions that may not be documented except under NDA.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The adoption of the JTAG standard helped move JTAG-centric debugging environments away from early processor-specific designs.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Processors can normally be halted, single stepped, or let run freely.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] One can set code breakpoints, both for code in RAM (often using a special machine instruction e.g., INT3) and in ROM/flash.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Data breakpoints are often available, as is bulk data download to RAM.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Most designs have *halt mode debugging*, but some allow debuggers to access registers and data buses without needing to halt the core being debugged.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Sometimes FPGA developers also use JTAG to develop debugging tools.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The same JTAG techniques used to debug software running inside a CPU can help debug other digital design blocks inside an FPGA.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] For example, custom JTAG instructions can be provided to allow reading registers built from arbitrary sets of signals inside the FPGA, providing visibility for behaviors that are invisible to boundary scan operations.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Similarly, writing such registers could provide controllability that is not otherwise available.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] JTAG allows device programmer hardware to transfer data into internal non-volatile device memory (e.g., CPLDs).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Some device programmers serve a double purpose for programming as well as debugging the device.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In the case of FPGAs, volatile memory devices can also be programmed via the JTAG port, normally during development work.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In addition, internal monitoring capabilities (temperature, voltage, and current) may be accessible via the JTAG port.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] JTAG programmers are also used to write software and data into flash memory.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] This is usually done using the same data bus access the CPU would use, and is sometimes handled by the CPU.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In other cases, the memory chips themselves have JTAG interfaces.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Some modern debug architectures provide internal and external bus master access without needing to halt and take over a CPU.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In the worst case, it is usually possible to drive external bus signals using the boundary scan facility.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] As a practical matter, when developing an embedded system, emulating the instruction store is the fastest way to implement the *debug cycle* (edit, compile, download, test, and debug).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] This is because the in-circuit emulator simulating an instruction store can be updated very quickly from the development host via, say, USB.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Using a serial UART port and bootloader to upload firmware to Flash makes this debug cycle quite slow and possibly expensive in terms of tools; installing firmware into Flash (or SRAM instead of Flash) via JTAG is an intermediate solution between these extremes.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] JTAG boundary scan technology provides access to a number of logic signals of a complex integrated circuit, including the device pins.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The signals are represented in the boundary scan register (BSR) accessible via the TAP.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] This permits testing as well as controlling the states of the signals for testing and debugging.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Therefore, both software and hardware (manufacturing) faults may be located and an operating device may be monitored.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] When combined with built-in self-test (BIST), the JTAG scan chain enables a low-overhead embedded solution to test an IC for certain static faults (shorts, opens, and logic errors).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The scan chain mechanism does not generally help diagnose or test for timing, temperature or other dynamic operational errors that may occur.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Test cases are often provided in standardized formats such as SVF, or its binary sibling XSVF, and used in production tests.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The ability to perform such testing on finished boards is an essential part of Design For Test in today's products, increasing the number of faults that can be found before products ship to customers.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] A JTAG interface is a special interface added to a chip.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Depending on the version of JTAG, two, four, or five pins are added.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The four and five-pin interfaces are designed so that multiple chips on a board can have their JTAG lines daisy-chained together if specific conditions are met.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The two-pin interface is designed so that multiple chips can be connected in a star topology.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In either case, a test probe needs only connect to a single JTAG port to have access to all chips on a circuit board.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The TRST pin is an optional active-low reset to the test logic, usually asynchronous, but sometimes synchronous, depending on the chip.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] If the pin is not available, the test logic can be reset by switching to the reset state synchronously, using TCK and TMS.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Note that resetting test logic doesn't necessarily imply resetting anything else.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] There are generally some processor-specific JTAG operations that can reset all or part of the chip being debugged.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Since only one data line is available, the protocol is serial.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] One bit of data is transferred in from TDI and out to TDO per TCK rising clock edge.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Instructions for typical ICs might read the chip ID, sample input pins, drive (or float) output pins, manipulate chip functions, or bypass (pipe TDI to TDO to logically shorten chains of multiple chips).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] As with any clocked signal, data presented to TDI must be valid for some chip-specific *Setup* time before and *Hold* time after the relevant (here, rising) clock edge.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] TDO data is valid for some chip-specific time after the falling edge of TCK.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The maximum operating frequency of TCK varies depending on all chips in the chain (the lowest speed must be used), but it is typically 10-100 MHz (100-10 ns per bit).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Also, TCK frequencies depend on board layout and JTAG adapter capabilities and state.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] One chip might have a 40 MHz JTAG clock, but only if it is using a 200 MHz clock for non-JTAG operations; and it might need to use a much slower clock when it is in a low-power mode.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Accordingly, some JTAG adapters have *adaptive clocking* using an RTCK (Return TCK) signal.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Faster TCK frequencies are most useful when JTAG is used to transfer large amounts of data, such as when storing a program executable into flash memory.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Clocking changes on TMS steps through a standardized JTAG state machine.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The JTAG state machine can reset, access an instruction register, or access data selected by the instruction register.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] JTAG platforms often add signals to the handful defined by the IEEE 1149.1 specification.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] A System Reset (SRST) signal is quite common, letting debuggers reset the whole system, not just the parts with JTAG support.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Sometimes, there are event signals used to trigger activity by the host or by the device being monitored through JTAG, or, perhaps, additional control lines.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Even though few consumer products provide an explicit JTAG port connector, the connections are often available on the printed circuit board as a remnant from development prototyping and/or production.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] When exploited, these connections often provide the most viable means for reverse engineering.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Reduced pin count JTAG uses only two wires, a clock wire and a data wire.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] This is defined as part of the IEEE 1149.7 standard.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The two-wire interface reduced pressure on the number of pins, and devices can be connected in a star topology.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The star topology enables some parts of the system to be powered down, while others can still be accessed over JTAG; a daisy chain requires all JTAG interfaces to be powered.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Other two-wire interfaces exist, such as Serial Wire Debug (SWD) and Spy-Bi-Wire (SBW).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In JTAG, devices expose one or more *test access ports* (TAPs).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The picture above shows three TAPs, which might be individual chips or might be modules inside one chip.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] A daisy chain of TAPs is called a *scan chain*, or (loosely) a target.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Scan chains can be arbitrarily long, but in practice, twenty TAPs is unusually long.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] To use JTAG, a host is connected to the target's JTAG signals (TMS, TCK, TDI, TDO, etc.) through some kind of *JTAG adapter*, which may need to handle issues like level shifting and galvanic isolation.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The adapter connects to the host using some interface such as USB, PCI, Ethernet, and so forth.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The host communicates with the TAPs by manipulating TMS and TDI in conjunction with TCK and reading results through TDO (which is the only standard host-side input).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] At a basic level, using JTAG involves reading and writing instructions and their associated data registers, and sometimes involves running a number of test cycles.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Behind those registers is hardware that is not specified by JTAG, and which has its own states that are affected by JTAG activities.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Most JTAG hosts use the shortest path between two states, perhaps constrained by quirks of the adapter.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] (For example, one adapter only handles paths whose lengths are multiples of seven bits.) Some layers built on top of JTAG monitor the state transitions and use uncommon paths to trigger higher-level operations.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Some ARM cores use such sequences to enter and exit a two-wire (non-JTAG) SWD mode.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] A Zero Bit Scan (ZBS) sequence is used in IEEE 1149.7 to access advanced functionality such as switching TAPs into and out of scan chains, power management, and a different two-wire mode.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Instruction register sizes tend to be small, perhaps four or seven bits wide.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Except for BYPASS and EXTEST, all instruction opcodes are defined by the TAP implementer, as are their associated data registers; undefined instruction codes should not be used.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] On exit from the RESET state, the instruction register is preloaded with either BYPASS or IDCODE.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] This allows JTAG hosts to identify the size and, at least partially, contents of the scan chain to which they are connected.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] (They can enter the RESET state, then scan the Data Register until they read back the data they wrote.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] A BYPASS register has only a zero bit, while an IDCODE register is 32 bits and starts with a one.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] So the bits not written by the host can easily be mapped to TAPs.) Such identification is often used to sanity-check manual configuration since IDCODE is often nonspecific.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] It could, for example, identify an ARM Cortex-M3-based microcontroller, without specifying the microcontroller vendor or model; or a particular FPGA, but not how it has been programmed.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] A common idiom involves shifting BYPASS into the instruction registers of all TAPs except one, which receives some other instruction.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] That way, all TAPs except one expose a single-bit data register, and values can be selectively shifted into or out of that one TAP's data register without affecting any other TAP.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The IEEE 1149.1 (JTAG) standard describes a number of instructions to support boundary scan applications.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Some of these instructions are *mandatory*, but TAPs used for debug instead of boundary scan testing sometimes provide minimal or no support for these instructions.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Devices may define more instructions, and those definitions should be part of a BSDL file provided by the manufacturer.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The path creates a virtual access capability that circumvents the normal inputs and outputs, providing direct control of the device and detailed visibility for signals.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The contents of the boundary scan register, including signal I/O capabilities, are usually described by the manufacturer using a part-specific BSDL file.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] These are used with design 'netlists' from CAD/EDA systems to develop tests used in board manufacturing.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Commercial test systems often cost several thousand dollars for a complete system and include diagnostic options to pinpoint faults such as open circuits and shorts.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] They may also offer schematic or layout viewers to depict the fault in a graphical manner.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] To enable boundary scanning, IC vendors add logic to each of their devices, including scan cells for each of the signal pins.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] These cells are then connected together to form the boundary scan shift register (BSR), which is connected to a TAP controller.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] These designs are parts of most Verilog or VHDL libraries.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] An example helps show the operation of JTAG in real systems.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The example here is the debug TAP of an ARM11 processor, the ARM1136 core.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The processor itself has extensive JTAG capability, similar to what is found in other CPU cores, and it is integrated into chips with even more extensive capabilities accessed through JTAG.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] This is a non-trivial example, which is representative of a significant cross section of JTAG-enabled systems.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In addition, it shows how control mechanisms are built using JTAG's register read/write primitives, and how those combine to facilitate testing and debugging complex logic elements; CPUs are common, but FPGAs and ASICs include other complex elements which need to be debugged.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Licensees of this core integrate it into chips, usually combining it with other TAPs as well as numerous peripherals and memory.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] One of those other TAPs handles boundary scan testing for the whole chip; it is not supported by the debug TAP.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] That scan chain modification is one subject of a forthcoming IEEE 1149.7 standard.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] That model resembles the model used in other ARM cores.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Non-ARM systems generally have similar capabilities, perhaps implemented using the Nexus protocols on top of JTAG, or other vendor-specific schemes.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Older ARM7 and ARM9 cores include an *EmbeddedICE* module which combines most of those facilities, but has an awkward mechanism for instruction execution: the debugger must drive the CPU instruction pipeline, clock by clock, and directly access the data buses to read and write data to the CPU.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The ARM11 uses the same model for trace support (ETM, ETB) as those older cores.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Newer ARM Cortex cores closely resemble this debug model, but build on a *Debug Access Port* (DAP) instead of direct CPU access.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In this architecture (named *CoreSight Technology*), core and JTAG module is completely independent.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] They are also decoupled from JTAG so they can be hosted over ARM's two-wire **SWD** interface (see below) instead of just the six-wire JTAG interface.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] (ARM takes the four standard JTAG signals and adds the optional TRST, plus the RTCK signal used for adaptive clocking.) The CoreSight JTAG-DP is asynchronous to the core clocks, and does not implement RTCK.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Also, the newer cores have updated trace support.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] One basic way to debug software is to present a single-threaded model, where the debugger periodically stops execution of the program and examines its state as exposed by register contents and memory (including peripheral controller registers).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] When interesting program events approach, a person may want to single-step instructions (or lines of source code) to watch how a particular misbehavior happens.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] So, for example, a JTAG host might HALT the core, entering debug mode, and then read CPU registers using ITR and DCC.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] After saving processor state, it could write those registers with whatever values it needs, then execute arbitrary algorithms on the CPU, accessing memory and peripherals to help characterize the system state.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] After the debugger performs those operations, the state may be restored and execution continued using the RESTART instruction.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Debug mode is also entered asynchronously by the debug module, triggering a watchpoint or breakpoint, or by issuing a BKPT (breakpoint) instruction from the software being debugged.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] When it is not being used for instruction tracing, the ETM can also trigger entry to debug mode; it supports complex triggers sensitive to state and history, as well as the simple address comparisons exposed by the debug module.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Asynchronous transitions to debug mode are detected by polling the DSCR register.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] This is how single stepping is implemented: HALT the core, set a temporary breakpoint at the next instruction or next high-level statement, RESTART, poll DSCR until you detect asynchronous entry to debug state, remove that temporary breakpoint, repeat.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Modern software is often too complex to work well with such a single-threaded model.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] For example, a processor used to control a motor (perhaps one driving a saw blade) may not be able to safely enter halt mode; it may need to continue handling interrupts to ensure physical safety of people and/or machinery.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Issuing a HALT instruction using JTAG might be dangerous.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] ARM processors support an alternative debug mode, called *Monitor Mode*, to work with such situations.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] This monitor communicates with the debugger using the DCC and could arrange, for example, to single step only a single process while other processes (and interrupt handlers) continue running.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Microprocessor vendors have often defined their own core-specific debugging extensions.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Such vendors include Infineon, MIPS with EJTAG, and more.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] If the vendor does not adopt a standard (such as the ones used by ARM processors or Nexus), they need to define their own solution.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] If they support boundary scan, they generally build debugging over JTAG.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Freescale has COP and OnCE (On-Chip Emulation).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] OnCE includes a JTAG command which makes a TAP enter a special mode where the IR holds OnCE debugging commands for operations such as single stepping, breakpointing, and accessing registers or memory.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] It also defines EOnCE (Enhanced On-Chip Emulation) presented as addressing real-time concerns.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Note that tracing is non-invasive; systems do not need to stop operating to be traced.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Nexus defines a processor debug infrastructure that is largely vendor-independent.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] It also defines a high-speed auxiliary port interface, used for tracing and more.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Nexus is used with some newer platforms, such as the Atmel AVR32 and Freescale MPC5500 series processors.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The target's JTAG interface is accessed using some JTAG-enabled application and some JTAG adapter hardware.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] There is a wide range of such hardware, optimized for purposes such as production testing, debugging high-speed systems, low-cost microcontroller development, and so on.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] In the same way, the software used to drive such hardware can be quite varied.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Software developers mostly use JTAG for debugging and updating firmware.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] There are no official standards for JTAG adapter physical connectors.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Development boards usually include a header to support preferred development tools; in some cases, they include multiple such headers because they need to support multiple such tools.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] For example, a microcontroller, FPGA, and ARM application processor rarely share tools, so a development board using all of those components might have three or more headers.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Production boards may omit the headers, or when space is limited, may provide JTAG signal access using test points.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Those connectors tend to include more than just the four standardized signals (TMS, TCK, TDI, TDO).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Usually, reset signals are provided, one or both of TRST (TAP reset) and SRST (system reset).
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The connector usually provides the board-under-test's logic supply voltage so that the JTAG adapters use the appropriate logic levels.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The board voltage may also serve as a *board present* debugger input.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Other event input or output signals may be provided, or general purpose I/O (GPIO) lines, to support more complex debugging architectures.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Higher end products frequently use dense connectors (frequently 38-pin MICTOR connectors) to support high-speed tracing in conjunction with JTAG operations.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] A recent trend is to have development boards integrate a USB interface to JTAG, where a second channel is used for a serial port.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] (Smaller boards can also be powered through USB.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Since modern PCs tend to omit serial ports, such integrated debug links can significantly reduce clutter for developers.) Production boards often rely on bed-of-nails connections to test points for testing and programming.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] There are both *dumb* adapters, where the host decides and performs all JTAG operations; and *smart* ones, where some of that work is performed inside the adapter, often driven by a microcontroller.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] The *smart* adapters eliminate link latencies for operation sequences that may involve polling for status changes between steps, and may accordingly offer higher throughput.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] As of 2018, adapters with a USB link from the host are the most common approach.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Higher-end products often support Ethernet, with the advantage that the debug host can be quite remote.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Adapters that support high-speed trace ports generally include several megabytes of trace buffer and provide high-speed links (USB or Ethernet) to get that data to the host.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Parallel port adapters are simple and inexpensive, but they are relatively slow because they use the host CPU to change each bit ("bit banging").
[src:design-for-test/jtag] They have declined in usefulness because most computers in recent years don't have a parallel port.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Driver support is also a problem because pin usage by adapters varies widely.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Since the parallel port is based on 5 V logic level, most adapters lacked voltage translation support for 3.3 V or 1.8 V target voltages.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] RS-232 serial port adapters also exist and are similarly declining in usefulness.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] They generally involve either slower bit banging than a parallel port or a microcontroller translating some command protocol to JTAG operations.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Such serial adapters are also not fast, but their command protocols could generally be reused on top of higher-speed links.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] With all JTAG adapters, software support is a basic concern.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Some vendors do not publish the protocols used by their JTAG adapter hardware, limiting their customers to the tool chains supported by those vendors.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] This is a particular issue for "smart" adapters, some of which embed significant amounts of knowledge about how to interact with specific CPUs.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Most development environments for embedded software include JTAG support.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] All such software tends to include basic debugger support: stopping, halting, single stepping, breakpoints, data structure browsing, and so on.
[src:design-for-test/jtag] Commercial tools tend to provide tools like very accurate simulators and trace analysis, which are not currently available as open source.
